title: Clip on Solidoodle anti-backlash well nut holder

description.text:
Updated version is out now!  It is still untested, but should work if you can't find any screws nearby.  
This is a holder for a well nut to prevent banding on Solidoodles with the aluminium bed.  No screws required! (I left the holes just in case)

This is untested, but should work now!

  • Insert well nut (5/16-in-18 x 3/4-in Rubber Standard (SAE) Well Nut: http://www.lowes.com/pd_137185-37672-880512_0__?productId=3012496)

  • Slide down the z threaded rod.

  • Slide the two large brace rods in the holes, they will be a tight fit!

  • Insert the thinner two braces on top of the large braces. These will likely need to be sanded down to fully slide through. (Again, a very tight fit)

  • Insert paper or any other sliced material inbetween the two sheets to create pressure holding the well nut down.
    • There must be adequet pressure on the well nut in order for it to help z-banding!

comments.text: I might be misunderstanding this but how do the brace rods fit all the way through? The underside of the Z screw isnt exposed on both sides
comments.author: Loves2Fail

comments.text: I modified this to go on just like the thing it was remixed from.  The brace rods should slide through the bottom two rectangular holes to keep the top in place.  Only the well nut should touch the threaded rod.  The braces will touch only the underside of the plate and the other printed part.  I used a well nut for a very short time before switching to a M3 threaded rod.  The .5mm pitch 100% eliminated my horizontal banding.

Thank you for uploading some pictures of your amazing print. Glad to see that all the details i put into the model can be printed that good! The decision of just using supports with the bells turned out to be helpful as I can see - thanks for the description.
I'm happy that you like what I've made out of this piece of architecture! :)
comments.author: cr1cr1

comments.text: Another comment: I remarked that even if tilted by 4° around the x axis, the tower is not perfectly straight. I've seen that from the slices produced by Cura: not totally identical along the perimeter.
comments.author: Chrisibub

comments.text:
You're welcome. This is one of my favorite prints!
Not sure if it's possible but a good solution would be to include some bell supports in the model directly, so that we do not need any support at all in the slicer ! The challenge is to make them easy to remove :-)
comments.author: Chrisibub

comments.text:
Thank you for letting me know about the problem with the 4°. I'll check that and correct it!
When designing, I've already thought abt the bells, nevertheless I decided not to add supports manual. But I'll make an updated second version with bell supports for the future makers to have the decision which one to take.

description.text: The directions for this project were to make a replica of ourselves using the laser cutter and eggbot. -vector: 8 speed
100 power
5000 frequency

50 power To make the head:

I'm thinking of a "Here's every mod I made to my now perfect Robo3D to make it "the perfect printer" for under $1k. I searched around and I found this site that has a super great wizard for custom glass. I chose a NeoCeram which is the EXACT same stuff that your electric range has over the halogen heating elements. This stuff holds it temper for ever even up to 1200c!!! Now a warning here as my glass piece cost a total of $90 ($15 of this was Fedex). Ya, I too cringed when it was time to enter the charge card info. But when the glass arrived and I did my first print, WOW I was SO impressed with how INCREDIBLY FLAT and sturdy this surface is. Every single print was coming out almost perfect!!! I actually was thinking, and still am, "I wish my glass would have broken a while ago!" I can't tell you how happy I am with this new glass. What this SSR does is detect when power is applied to the low voltage side, it allows the high voltage to pass through. So the same electronics circuit that powered the old 12 volt heater is hijacked to control the more powerful 110v, 600w heater. I now have a bed heater that is ready LONG before the Hotend is! really! and I have a E3Dv6! http://reprap.org/wiki/PID_Tuning

The Tiered Pencil Holder is a three level multi-use storage unit. It can hold up to twenty-four pens or pencils, and has an entire different section on the top that can hold whatever you please. The pencil holes are one inch deep, so as to hold them in a way that is easily accessible to he student using it. The top hole is larger and deeper, so it can hold other tools that aren't used as often. The bottom tier has sixteen pencil-holes, the middle has eight, and the top tier has one large pencil-hole. The whole design is one piece, is only four and a half inches high, and five inches wide.

Objecives While using this design, students would be able to learn how to evaluate dimensions of real objects, and use that knowledge while making the design. Students can also learn the importance of making something useful. Yes, it's fun to print toys and trinkets, but you can really appreciate 3-dimensional printing when you make something you use every day. Audiences This design can be made by just about anyone. If you know how to use the proper tools, you can definitely make this. The actual design itself can be used by anyone as well. Preparation Before starting this project, students should have, at least, a basic knowledge about the following things:
-How to:
Extrude
Intrude
Fillet
& Sketch basic shapes
-Use Inventor (or any other application fr 3D printing) and be able to print it.
-The dimensions for this project are 4.5 inches high, and 5 inches wide, so make sure your printer can fit that. (or you could always make it smaller, but I do not recommend doing so) Steps 1.) Make a 5x5" square & Extrude it 1.5" upwards
2.) Put .4" circles around the edges (16)
3.) Make a 3.5x3.5 square in the middle of the first square & Extrude it 1.5"
4.) Put .4" circles around the edges (8)
5.) Intrude (reverse Extrude or cut) all 24 circles 1.5" deep
6.) Make a 1.5x1.5 square in the center of the middle tier and Extrude it 1.5"
7.) Make a 1.2" (or smaller) circle on the top & final tier
8.) Intrude the circle 3" deep (Don't worry, since it's right in the center, it won't run into anything)
9.) Fillet the edges, corners, and rim of holes. (I did .15", but you can you can Fillet it however much you please)
10.) Change the color! Default is boring... REQUIREMENTS
  • The maximum number of pencil-holes on the bottom tier is sixteen. There is no minimum.
  • The maximum number of pencil-holes on the middle tier is eight, and there is no minimum.
  • There can only be one pencil-hole in the top tier. Otherwise it would be too crowded, but if you like, you can make it like the other holes instead of the deeper and larger one in this particular design.
    • Results By the end of this project, you should find that your skill level in Filleting and analyzing real dimensions, have gone significantly up.
    It is difficult to tell how much to Fillet. Do you make the entire design rounded? Or do you leave it sharp and flat? While making this design, if you choose to Fillet the edges, there will come a time in the process where you need to figure out how much you would like to Fillet the design.
    Many projects do not involve using real objects. With this project, however, you will have to analyze the dimensions of a pencil, pen, or other writing tool, and find out how big or small you need to make the piece of your project that involves real objects.

description.text: I wanted to make a fast, easy-to-assemble version of ladybugbot, http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:12975. The last design required two printed parts--a top shell and bottom base. I'd have to print them separately, insert the motor, and hot glue them together. I figured that that should go, so I made a single shell with holes to drop in my motors and a wider slot to insert my electronics. The goal is a five minute drop-in assembly. I'd love to go faster, but I don't think that'll happen until I have a PCB next week. So, this is the updated, fast-to-print, fast-to-assembly 'bot shell. It prints on my TOM in 45 minutes (I recommend raftless for a better bottom finish) I don't have any video of this exact iteration running (I haven't soldered together the electronics yet), but there's a cute video of its parent thing scooting around my floor here: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=T493fRskCPA&feature=feedu

To assemble, drop your vibrating motors into the square holes in the bottom of the shell.  My motors are .26" in diameter and .72" long.  I route the motor wires inside the shell, through the little holes in either sie of the motor cavities.  Hold the motor in place with some hot glue--be sure that the vibrating shaft has room to spin.  Your electronics can go inside the shell however you like.  Hot glue the toothbrush heads on over the motors, again, making sure that the motor shafts have clearance, and you're ready to go!

  • Widened the smooth rod clamp so that it would grip more of the rod and hold better.
  • Added an extra hole for the contact switch.
  • Integrated a built-in spacer for holding the contact switch at the correct distance from the smooth rod.
  • Tapered the clamp opening so that it was less likely to break when putting on the smooth bar.
  • Counter-sunk all the bolt heads so that there is enough clearance to use on the Y axis
